<div class="header">
  <h1>Second Thoughts</h1>
  <h2 style="padding: 150px; color: #ebdfcf; font-size: 20px;">Looking at the mundane and the obvious, with a new set of eyes.<br><br>
Hello there! Welcome to my website! This is a way of mapping my journey through my studio 'Second Thoughts', here you will find things that I navigated through in this studio, how I shaped my thought process, what were the things I learned as well as some things that I un-learned, all mapped out through this webpage that you are on. This is a completely 'hand-coded' webpage with each and every letter, paragraph, colour, image seen here has been coded by me. I've used HTML and CSS to create this page.<br><br>
The contents on this page have been divided into three main categories: namely;
<ul>
  <li>What gives me Second Thoughts</li>
  <li>What I realized</li>
  <li>How I translated these learnings into my practice</li>
</ul><br><br>
You can go through these sections from the top to bottom, or visit any of these specific sections by clicking on the links in the navigation bar down below.<br><br>
So come take a scroll and have some Second Thoughts!

  </h2>
</div>

<div class="topnav">
  <a href="#section1">What gives me Second thoughts</a>
  <a href="#section2">What I realized</a>
  <a href="#section3">How I translated these learnings into my practice</a>
</div>
</div>
<h4 id="section1" style="background-color: ivory;">What gives me Second thoughts</h4>
<div class="row">
<div class="column side">
    <h3>Using a lens to observe objects around us.</h3>
    <p style="font-family: 'Roboto';font-size: 16px;"> The idea of 'Re-looking' was practiced from the start, which lead to uncovering some really interesting insights for me. For example the fact that we use a mirror almost every day, it acts like a piece of self reflection for us, we stand in front of it, dress up, etc. but at the same time, it morphs our existing reality into something different than what we see. Yet we somehow let it have a huge impact on the way we walk and talk, how we present ourselves.
      <br><br><br><br><br><br><img src="mirror.jpg" width="300" height="300"></p>
  </div>
  
  <div class="column middle">
    <h3 style="color: white;">Re-Imagine. Re-create. Re-look, Investigate.</h3><br><br>
    <p style="font-family: 'Roboto';font-size: 16px; color: white;"> In the process of this studio, the idea of giving second thoughts to things was developed for me. Initially I had a very mixed understanding of what exactly giving ‘Second thought’ to things means.<br><br><br>

I often associated ‘Second thoughts’ with unsureness, confusion and used in the context of something negative.<br><br>
The words written above, I read in the abstract of the studio, and that left me thinking about the importance of these words in the situation we are in today. With COVID-19, many businesses shutdown, lot of people lost their source of daily income, many were left stranded in unknown cities, the problem of social distancing became more evident in a country with a large population. These were just some of my initial thoughts when reading through the abstract.<br><br><img src="mug.jpg" width="300" height="300" class="center"><br><br>
This activity showed how in order to change or 'Re-Imagine' systems to bring about system changes, one needs to understand the existing system in detail.
 
 </p>
  </div><br><br><br><br>

  <div class="column side">
    <h3>Finding some interesting observations</h3>
    <p style="font-family: 'Roboto';font-size: 16px;">
      When I observed 'TIME' through this lens, I could see how something so large, continous and beyond a human beings control, has been compressed to something as tiny as milliseconds and microseconds to suite our human needs. To make our lives more 'structured' and more 'defined', yet we often fail to follow something so arbitrary as time.<br>For us, growth is defined by time, an interestingly, there is no universal common time for humans, instead we have further divided time into timezones for each different continent!
      <br><br><br><img src="time.jpg" width="300" height="300"></p><br><br>
  </div><br><br>

<h3 style="padding: 20px;text-align: center; color: tomato;">How does a lens like this, the one that allows me to look at these minute observations, would help me create newer systems and services? Can it lead me to uncover some hidden details of something like an existing system?</h3><br><br>

<h4 id="section2">What I realized</h4>
<div class="row">
<div class="column side">
    <h3>Investigating the hidden 'gimmicks' and truths of a seemingly attractive product.</h3>
    <p style="font-family: 'Roboto';font-size: 16px;"> <img src="mood2.jpg" width="300" height="300"></p>
  </div>
  
  <div class="column middle">
    <h3 style="color: white;">The Age of Colonialization: Why Second thoughts are needed</h3>
    <p style="font-family: 'Roboto';font-size: 16px; color: white;">
       
       One particular activity in the class which involved us going through a moodboard, that provided visual pleasure and made me hungry at the same time too as it was a moodboard of food! The idea was to categorize these tempting foods based on their look, their presentation, their health benefits, etc. Which was a very fun thing to do, but the insights I took from this, left me pretty skeptical about the things I consume myself everyday, what I think is healthy for me or not.<br><br><br>
       Seemingliy attractive products and services in fact acted as a cloak to cover up some of the unethtical practices in its production process.

I  could see how things we percieved visually, the way they were presented to us, had a large impact on the way we felt about them. A nicely decorated, colourful product would be more appealing to a customer, over its competitor, which might lack these visual features. </strong><br><br><br>
<h3>But this led me to think, how do these problems go unnoticed by consumers? What makes them simply invisible to the eyes of the consumer?</h3><br><br>
<p style="font-family: 'Roboto';font-size: 16px; color: white;">When buying a new phone, what catches my eyes, is the features, the design, the camera and things like that, I do not look at the where the materials come from, where the phone is made, who makes this phone. Why am I so indifferent to these things even though they play such a big role in making that phone?

      <br><br><br>
       <h3>How can I look at this aspect of using human 'behavior' and bring this into my practice as a designer?<br><br><br>
    
    </h3></p>
      
  </div><br>

  <div class="column side">
    <h3>Studying brand identities, what makes them appeal to people.</h3><br>
    <p style="font-family: 'Google Sans';font-size: 16px;"><img src="real.jpg" width="300" height="300"><br><br>When seeing pictures like these, the first thing that catches my eyes is the luxury and comfort. These pictures make me want to live in such homes. But the larger problems of the real estate industry, similarly the fact that so many in the world lack even a basic roof over their heads is neglected by me.</p><br><br><br><br>
  </div>
</div><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>

<h3 style="padding: 30px;text-align: center;color: black; font-size: 50px;"><i>"There is no such thing as neutral design."</i></h3>
<p style="text-align: left; font-family: Google Sans; padding-left: 1200px;">-Richard Thaler</p><br><br>

<div class=" column side" style="text-align: center;">
  <p style="font-family: Google Sans; font-size: 20px; color: white;">Small changes or additions in the design change the 'IMPACT' of the design.</p></div>

<div class=" column middle" style="text-align: center;">
  <p style="font-family: Google Sans; font-size: 20px; color: white;">System Elements, when changed can cause CULTURAL changes.</p></div>

